statement.title: Problem Description
statement.content: jrMz has two types of angles, one type of angle is an interior angle of $n$-sided regular polygon, and the other type of angle is an interior angle of $m$-sided regular polygon. jrMz wants to use them to make up an angle of 360 degrees, which means, jrMz needs to choose some or none of the angles which belong to the first type and some or none of the angles which belong to the second type so that the sum value of the angles chosen equals 360 degrees. But jrMz doesn��t know whether it is possible, can you help him?

statement.title: Input
statement.content:
The first line contains an integer $T\left(1\leq T\leq10\right)$����The number of the test cases.
For each test case, the only line contains two integers $n,m\left(1\leq n,m\leq100\right)$ with a white space separated.

statement.title: Output
statement.content: For each test case, the only line contains a integer that is the answer.

statement.title: Sample Output
statement.content:
Yes
Yes
No


Hint

In test case 1, jrMz can choose 1 angle which belongs to the first type and 2 angles which belong to the second type, because 90+135+135=360.
In test case 2, jrMz can choose 6 angles which belong to the first type, because6\times60=360.
In test case 3, jrMz can��t make up an angle of 360 degrees.
